edding Base64 seems essential, but perhaps using `javac` would be easier for generating a byte array. I'm trying to clarify if the instruction to not compile or run tests limits us to just generating a class file. It might be better to create a valid class file with Python while keeping it maintainable.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kZUKs2940v1f0iWZgoQ3UAaM|fc_02a636a2e022bdda0169f61c615a5881a1b4839721e51e9b1d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); mkdir -p \"$tmp/parallelworld\"; cat > \"$tmp/parallelworld/LoadedFixture.java\" <<'EOF'\npackage parallelworld;\npublic class LoadedFixture {\n}\nEOF\njavac --release 8 \"$tmp/parallelworld/LoadedFixture.java\"\nbase64 -w0 \"$tmp/parallelworld/LoadedFixture.class\"\nrm -rf \"$tmp\"", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2195, "output": 1797, "cacheRead": 14848, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 18840, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777736776211, "responseId": "resp_02a636a2e022bdda0169f61c488ed081a1bbecec74b142b5b0"}}
